title: Introduction to R
description:
Based on the survey results and the recommendations during the inaugural meeting, we decided to make our next meeting a workshop for a basic introduction to R.

Bring your laptop, extension cord (if you have battery issues), and your enthusiasm. You are welcome to come if you have NEVER used R before, and you are welcome to come if you use R every day. Advanced users will have plenty of opportunities to help beginners with debugging. We will be learning collaboratively.

Prior to the meetup, please download the latest version of R and RStudio on your laptop (in that order). Below are the links for downloads

https://cran.rstudio.com/

https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/

Since we plan to have refreshments at this meetup, we kindly ask you to RSVP only if you are *sure* that you will be coming. At the last meetup, we ended up with too much food because fewer people came than RSVPed, and we‚Äôd prefer not to have the same problem this time.

title: Machine Learning with R
description:
UPDATES: Materials are now up on my git repo https://github.com/ksasso/MLmodels_inR_GDG2017

git clone to make a copy OR download a zip of all the files by navigating to the green "Clone or Download" button in the right hand corner and selecting "Download Zip"

THERE WILL BE PIZZA thanks to the Columbus Collaboratory!

At this meet up Katie Sasso will provide a crash course on implementing some of the most popular machine learning algorithms and techniques. Specific topics may include Decision Trees, ensemble methods (gradient boosting vs. bagging/bootstrapping), Random Forests, and Neural Networks. Attendees can expect a very high-level overview of techniques, a review of the circumstances under which they are and aren't appropriate for use, and a brief crash course on how to implement each using R!

Please note:

This meetup is not appropriate for very beginner level R users, we expect you to be familiar with fundamental R objects and functions.

title: Introduction to Shiny App
description:
Jim Hughes, a visiting PhD student from University of South Australia offered to give a Shiny App workshop. Join us to learn more about Shiny apps!

Get materials here:

https://www.dropbox.com/sh/o5zgygc5aoor36z/AABI0oDi8ObIa18cziV5-Q4sa?dl=0

With the use of the Shiny package for the R programming language, users are able to make interactive web applications that can be a powerful tool for sharing and communication of research. The package provides tools for shaping a user-interface and providing reactive elements dependent on user input. This is all achieved while maintaining the functionality and flexibility of R. This 2 hour workshop will serve as an introduction to the Shiny framework, demonstrating some of its uses. It will include hands-on coding, so feel free to bring a charged laptop with R and RStudio installed.

title: Easy data cleaning and manipulation with tidyverse
description:
We will be talking about tidyr & dplyr packages, and show how these packages make data cleaning much less painful & provide easy to use functions for the first steps of data exploration. After a short presentation about "tidy data" and tidyr & dplyr, we will do practical examples and go over the vignettes provided by Hadley Wickham (the creator of the tidyverse).

Bring your laptop, extension cord (if you have battery issues), and your enthusiasm! Although tidyverse doesn't require much R experience, we expect you to be familiar with R, RStudio, loading data & packages into R and basic understanding of base R class types.

tidyr examples require certain data files so:

- Please download them via dropbox from here (https://www.dropbox.com/sh/nkhrhcgx6ogg24j/AACKLaJq5_8VDQHmlhZfluCOa?dl=0)

- Or if you're familiar with GitHub get it from the tidy repo (https://github.com/tidyverse/tidyr) under vignettes.

Since we plan to have refreshments at this meetup, we kindly ask you to RSVP only if you are sure that you will be coming.

title: useR2018! Conference Recap and Highlights
description:
Details
Please bring your laptop and have R and RStudio (and the tidyverse package) installed and working. But if things don't work and you're having issues, don't worry! We're here to help (‚óï‚Äø‚óï‚úø)

Couldn't make it to Australia for this year's #useR2018 Conference? No worries! RLadies Columbus has got you covered. At this meet up I (Katie) am going to share some of the "best" content from useR. We will cover several of the session talks and a few of the paid tutorials at a super high-level; with my goal being at the end to take a vote of attendees and pick one of the topics to dive deeper on at an upcoming RLadies. I hope to cover (~5 mins each) most of the following: gganimate package and keynote talk, glue package and talk, Roger Peng Beyond Syntax keynote talk, Fable and Fasster forecasting packages and talks, SEER package and talk, Jenny Bryan's Code Smells and Feels talk and key functions learned, MGCV/Beyond Linearity tutorial and content, Max Kuhn recipes package tutorial and content. Goal is to give attendees enough info such that they could go home, watch talk, and walk through any associated materials and tutorials on their own. Other goal: choose one of the packages associated with a talk or tutorial to dive deeper on together at a future RLadies.

title: Using Git with RStudio Projects
description:
Please bring your laptop and have R and RStudio installed and working. But if things don't work and you're having issues, don't worry! We're here to help (‚óï‚Äø‚óï‚úø)

About this meetup:

We will talk about the basics of version control with Git, and how this sometimes painful looking process can be made easy with RStudio projects.

Although anything you'll learn in this class can be used with any Git web repository, I'll mainly show examples via GitHub. If you don't have one yet please create an account on https://github.com/

git

https://git-scm.com/docs/gittutorial

I don't yet have materials for this class, but it will be posted on my GitHub page: https://github.com/karaesmen and I will let you know which repository we will be using during class.

title: Shiny meets Electron:  Turn your Shiny app into a standalone desktop app!
description:
Please bring your laptop and have R and RStudio (and the tidyverse package) installed and working. But if things don't work and you're having issues, don't worry! We're here to help (‚óï‚Äø‚óï‚úø)

About this meetup:

Using Shiny in consulting can be challenging, as all deployment options involve either sending intellectual property and data to the cloud or IT involvement. When providing consultative like services to extremely large, risk-averse, enterprises this can greatly restrict one‚Äôs ability to quickly get Shiny apps into users‚Äô hands, as engagement of IT can take months if approved at all. We‚Äôll share how the Columbus Collaboratory team overcame these barriers to rapid deployment by coupling R Portable and Electron, a framework for creating native applications with a variety of web technologies. All the tools needed to use Electron for desktop deployment of Shiny apps will be reviewed. We‚Äôll highlight a specific example in which these technologies were used within a large enterprise to completely automate a weekly report. We‚Äôll also share how the app used R Packages such as openxlsx, shinydashboard, RODBC, and Zoo to query an internal database, cleanse data, calculate key metrics, and create a downloadable excel file for dissemination. The best part? This Shiny app was delivered to the end business user as a stand-alone executable.

title: Debugging in RStudio
description:
‚Ä¢ What we'll do
When you are building R scripts and documents, it can be challenging to figure out what went wrong when the code behaves in unexpected ways. Fortunately, there are excellent tools built into R and RStudio that can make debugging easier. This talk will explore those tools, including: using base R functions for debugging, tracing techniques, setting breakpoints in RStudio, understanding debug mode, and troubleshooting more complicated sources like packages and Shiny applications.

‚Ä¢ What to bring
Charged laptop and your enthusiasm!

‚Ä¢ Important to know

This meetup is not appropriate for very beginner level R users, we expect you to be familiar with fundamental R objects and functions.

title: New advancements to tidyr package: Good riddance Gather and Spread!
description:
We've had a lot of sessions on the very important steps of tidying data (what some call "denormalized" data in database land). Tidy data is essential for all things modeling and visualization. The tidyr package offers several functions for reproducible and fast tidying, but two of the main ones (gather and spread) were a bit tricky to use!

Join us as we walk through key updates to the tidyr package, namely the new pivot_longer and pivot_wider functions. These functions are designed to be far more user friendly and robust than their old counter parts.

Please come with a machine that can access rstudio.cloud. Katie will share link to project prior to session.

title: useR2019! Recap and overview of the latest and greatest
description:
Couldn't make it to Toulouse, France for useR2019!? No worries, we've got you covered! After a brief hiatus R-Ladies Columbus is back. Katie & Ezgi will be recapping learnings from the conference on all the latest and greatest in tidy data, shiny, modeling, and more. Katie will make an RStudio cloud link available ahead of the meet-up with a link to the presentation and demos. We will do our best to cover some talks and content that may be harder to find online (like awesome posters and lightning talks).
One goal of the session will be to vote on one topic featured in order to dive into deeper in a future workshop style meet up (hate gather and spread? learn about pivot_longer and pivot_wider and vote for that to be covered in a future meet-up)!

As always pizza and soft drinks will be available courtesy of our great local supporter, the Columbus Collaboratory.

Parking: Park in any spot marked "Reserved for the Columbus Collaboratory". There should be more than enough available- all are free. If you find that these spots are filled - park anywhere in surrounding lots and Katie will give you a day pass for your dashboard. See pics below for directions.

title: Introduction to RMarkdown
description:
We will go over the RMarkdown introduction on the RStudio website.
Simply go to https://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/lesson-1.html to see the material. If you don't know what RMarkdown is, just watch the introductory video in the link!

Please bring your laptop and sign up to RStudio Cloud at https://rstudio.cloud/ if you haven't done so already. Simply sign in to RStudio Cloud on the day of the meetup, then links containing example code throughout the introduction will open easily on your browser! title: Hierarchical and Partitioning clustering in R
description:
Blythe Moreland will go through some of the faster methods for hierarchical and partitioning clustering and then spend some time on network visualization, such as igraph or visNetwork.

Blythe is a post-doctoral scientist working in the translational bioinformatics group at the Institute for Genomic Medicine at Nationwide Children's Hospital. She works with biologists, informatics analysts, and computer scientists, in part to study how genetic variants can indirectly affect protein formation or protein binding, and be linked to human diseases.

Materials will be available on R-Ladies github under meetup presentations repo of our chapter (https://github.com/rladies/meetup-presentations_columbus) on the day of the meetup.

title: Data visualization with ggplot2 üìäüìà- Vol 2
description:
Since no one came forward to host this meetup (yes ladies, this time I am totally fine being the bad cop, and will pick someone... üòà) I will present some ggplot2 material I had from before.

For those who are less familiar with ggplot2:
It is a wonderful and very popular data visualization package in R. It provides all sorts of functions to customize any bits and pieces you can imagine in a plot.

Beginners are welcome, although some familiarity with R is needed. And if you are used to plotting with base R plot, I'd say it's time to spice things up with ggplot2!

In our last ggplot2 meetup we mainly talked about point (scatter) plots. I will pick up from there, show a more customized example and move on to plotting:
- histograms
- barplots
- boxplots
- doxplots
- errorbars

I know it's a little ambitious, so please let's all try to get there in time. (I'll try to do my best too üòÖ)

Materials will be available on R-Ladies github under meetup presentations repo of our chapter (https://github.com/rladies/meetup-presentations_columbus) on the day of the meetup.

Please bring your laptop and have R and RStudio (and the tidyverse package) installed and working. But if things don't work and you're having issues, don't worry! We're here to help (‚óï‚Äø‚óï‚úø)

And we'll have pizza! üçï

title: Harmonizing Docker and R
description:
This month we will take a short break from tidymodels and talk about containerization with Docker!

Dr. Stephanie LaHaye will introduce us to the world of Docker and will highlight the key reasons why Docker is an excellent and integral tool for anyone aiming to make their code more reproducible and shareable, and why it is essential when sharing to users in outside environments. We will learn how to launch Docker, check for images on our local systems, push and pull from Docker Hub, create a basic Dockerfile, and finally use it to run an Rscript.

Before the presentation, please install Docker by following the instructions for
- mac (https://docs.docker.com/mac/step_one/)
- linux (https://docs.docker.com/linux/step_one/)
- windows (https://docs.docker.com/get-started/)

Stephanie will be presenting from her Mac and she will be using Mac Docker Desktop (https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-mac/install/).

You can find the meetup materials at: https://github.com/sdl002/R_Docker_Intro

Stephanie is a Senior Bioinformatics Scientist at the Institute for Genomic Medicine at Nationwide Children‚Äôs Hospital in Columbus, Ohio. She attended Michigan State University for her undergraduate work where she received a bachelor of science in Genomics and Molecular Genetics and a bachelor of science in Human Biology. She then attended the Ohio State University for her PhD in Molecular Genetics, where she focused on cardiovascular genomics research. After graduate school Stephanie did a postdoc at the Institute for Genomic Medicine, focusing on the development of automated pipelines using serverless technology to handle next generation sequencing data for pediatric cancer patients.

title: R-Ladies Columbus Monthly Meetup: Web Analytics Wednesdays Crossover Event!
description:
A Crossover Event with Web Analytics Wednesdays (WAW)!: R Meets Digital Analytics (Hands-on!)

This month‚Äôs event will be a crossover with the WAW meetup! We will be mostly following the R-Ladies format, which means you can easily follow along with the speaker (Katie) she works through some code exploring a digital analytics data set. The WAW crew will bring the expertise on all things digital attribution and analytics to add some color to this particular business problem.

No previous coding experience is required in order for you to follow along! We will be using RStudio Cloud, which is a free, browser-based environment, so be sure to sign up for an account prior to the meetup.

Link to RStudio Cloud project: https://rstudio.cloud/project/1443232

About Web Analytics Wednesdays
Web Analytics Wednesdays are an opportunity for digital analysts, digital marketers, and anyone who is interested in learning more about digital analytics to get together and share their experiences. And strengthen the central Ohio digital marketing community in the process!
All of our Columbus WAWs are free of charge thanks to the generosity of our sponsors: Clarivoy, TeamBuilder Search, InfoTrust, and Claravine. While lately events have been online - be sure to follow WAW closely as there in-person events offer great opportunities for networking and connecting with digital analytics practitioners and leaders (plus - tasty food and beverages!)

for more info please visit cbuswaw.com

title: Shiny Enterprise Applications
description:
This month we are thrilled to have Dr. Connie Brett!

She will be talking about Shiny Enterprise Applications - considerations for success and tools to get it done right.

This will be a virtual meetup, so please scroll down to see the details about how to join the call!

Connie will present in detail the challenges of designing and developing shiny applications for larger scaling and sharing (for example in an enterprise setting). She will talk in detail about scoping, planning, and tools for meeting these needs. The periscope R package will be introduced and used in a demonstration to show you how to start a shiny application that makes meeting these challenges easier so you can focus on the content of your application.

Connie is the CEO, Founder, and Principal Data Scientist of Aggregate Genius Inc. located in British Columbia, Canada. She is responsible for analytics oversight as well as delivering on the corporate vision backing the "Know what you KNOW" philosophy of the company. She delivers demonstrations, concept proofs, statistical models, feasibility studies, and productionalized architectures centered around big-data and analytics products.

Before founding Aggragate Genius, she received her B.A from Knox College followed by an M.S. and Ph.D. from The Ohio State University in computational chemistry. So even though she's now settled in Canada, she has some roots in Columbus, OH! After 20 years focusing on producing solid analytical models, software and visualization tools, as well as custom IT solutions architecture, she also became an entrepreneur with Aggragate Genius. We asked her to also talk a little bit about her career path as well and will provide some time for career related questions from the audience.

title: R-Ladies Columbus Monthly Meetup - Tidymodels!!!
description:
Let's get started with the tidymodels ecosystem together!! We will all learn how to get started with tidymodels, by working together through their 5 "starter" articles https://www.tidymodels.org/start/

The tidymodels framework is a collection of packages for modeling and machine learning using tidyverse principles. The tidymodels team has been hard at work over the past year plus building packages that building and training models easier and more streamlined. We've been super excited about it for a while and the great documentation we are so lucky to have from the tidyverse is now hitting the press - so let's learn about it together!

Be patient with us - we are learning :) Katie will open up RStudio Cloud, and work through tutorials 1-5 linked above. We encourage you all to do the same on your machines and let's just bring up questions and dive deeper as we go! Ezgi, our resident expert will be standing by to jump in when Katie goes off the rails ;)

title: R-Ladies Columbus Monthly Meetup
description:
Sentiment Analysis!
___________________________________________________________________________________
The Objective is to create a neural network that can predict if a given movie review is positive or negative. This type of computation is also called Sentiment Analysis.

I will be working with ‚ÄúIMDB data-set‚Äù, a set of 50,000 reviews from the Internet Movie Database. They are split into 25,000 reviews for training and 25,000 reviews for testing, each set consisting in 50% negative and 50% positive reviews.

I will use Keras library to build neural network and walk you through building and training model, model tuning with different hyper-parameter (Optimizer, Loss Function, No. of layers, epoch, batch_size ). I will try and improve the accuracy of model by experimenting with different hyper-parameters.

title: R-Ladies Columbus Monthly Meetup
description:
This month we will be hearing about a wide range of practical applications of R in the agronomy field!

Dr. Marin Harbur will be introduce her work with machine learning and Shiny applications. She will then provide an introduction to the use of spatial statistics in R. This will include map projections, the spatial features (sf) package, and kriging (interpolating) data using stars datasets. She will also show how to present spatial data using the leaflet package.

Marin is a Senior Data Analyst at Winfield United, the crop inputs division of Land O Lakes. She is also an Assistant Teaching Professor in the Department of Agronomy at Iowa State University, where she teaches Agronomy 513, Quantitative Methods in Agronomy. She graduated from Iowa State in 2003, where she co-majored in Crop Production and Physiology and Ecology and Evolutionary Biology. Marin lives in Lima Ohio with her wife, Kathleen, and two sons.
